Comment.Text: Finally, the feature vectors are classifier with an LDA classifier. Note that the probability vector of the classifier is sent to the Graz Visulization box for feedback ! In order to display correct feedback, the Graz Visulization box expects a two-dimensional input describing probabilities of each class.

Then comes the feature extraction part. The signal is filtered in the alpha/beta [8 24] Hz range. The filtered signal is then splitted in blocks of 1 second every 16th second and the logarithmic band power is computed thanks to the two Simple DSP and the Signal Average boxes. The matrices can then be converted in feature vectors. note: depending on what frequency range reacts best for the subject, you may have to tune this part of the scenario
You can browse each box' documentation by selecting the box and pressing F1

Overview This scenario demonstrates Motor Imagery with incremental learning. Its based on the original offline-trained scenario by Yann Renard and Fabien Lotte. note: the recorded files go to the folder where the scenario xml is located (${Player_ScenarioDirectory}/).

The preprocessing of this scenario consists in re-referencing all the channels to the channel 2 (which was located on the nose) and to select the 10 channels over the motor cortex of the hands. The Spatial Filter box computes a surface laplacian filter and reduces the output to two channels: one on the left and one on the right. note: depending on your acquisition device, you may have to tune this part of the scenario
